ing, scandal-ridden mayor, Rob Ford, and his brother Doug. In the penultimate chapter, the authors examine how Torontonians viewed their elected officials, and the city’s performance, two years after the election. McGregor, Moore, and Stephenson conclude with a reflection on what the analysis of Toronto 2014 says about voters in large cities in general, and provide a short epilogue addressing the 2018 election results. Written in an accessible style, this is the first book on the politics of Toronto during the Ford era that focuses on the perspective of the voter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLocal electionszOntariozToronto. 0aMayorszOntariozTorontoxElection. 0aPolitical campaignszOntariozToronto. 0aPolitical candidateszOntariozToronto. 0aVotingzOntariozToronto. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh1 aMoore, Aaron Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStephenson, Laura Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107392200 cprintz978148750963740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148750965140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487509651423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487509651/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles